<font size=3D"4">
<font color=3D"#000099"><b>
<p>A pyramid is a geometric solid, having a polygon as its base (or bottom)=
, with triangles for its faces (or sides) and a vertex that is perpendicula=
r to the base.<br>
The polygon base can have any number of sides, 3 or greater.</p><p>
A pyramid gets its name from its polygon base and <i>not</i> from its faces=
.<br>=20
So, the diagram at the top of this page depicts a square pyramid.
The diagrams below show a triangular pyramid and a pentagonal pyramid.<br>

<img src=3D"https://www.1728.org/pyramid3.png">&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://ww=
w.1728.org/pyrmdpnt.png">

<font color=3D"000099">
</font></p><p><font color=3D"000099">

<!-- L E F T   S I D E ----------------------------------------------------=
----- -->


<font face=3D"Arial"><font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"4"><b>

Like the diagram at the <i>top</i> of the page, the Great Pyramid of Egypt =
has a square base and 4 triangular faces and=20
that's what most people think of when they hear the word 'pyramid'.<br>
However, mathematically speaking, the base could have any number of sides,=
=20
3 or greater.

</b></font></font></font></font></p><p><font color=3D"000099"><font face=3D=
"Arial"><font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"4"><b>

